    <div class="ar20">
      <div class="container">
        <h1>Article 20: Protection in respect of conviction for offences</h1>
        <p>
          *Article 20 provides important protections to ensure that people are
          treated fairly and justly by the legal system. It prevents the abuse
          of legal procedures and safeguards the rights of individuals.
        </p>
        <p>
          By prohibiting ex-post facto laws, double jeopardy, and
          self-incrimination, Article 20 prevents the state from misusing its
          power to unfairly convict or punish individuals.
        </p>
        <p>
          Article 20 safeguards the freedom and rights of individuals,
          especially those accused of crimes, by ensuring that legal proceedings
          are conducted in a fair and just manner.
        </p>
        <p>
          * In Simple Words Article 20 provides essential protections to
          individuals accused of crimes, ensuring they are not unfairly treated
          by the legal system. It prevents the government from punishing someone
          for something that wasn’t a crime when they did it, stops them from
          being tried twice for the same offense, and protects them from being
          forced to confess. This helps maintain justice and fairness in legal
          proceedings.
        </p>
      </div>
    </div>
    <div class="seccontainer">
      <div class="container">
        <h1>Article 21: Protection of life and personal liberty</h1>
        <p>
          *Article 21 of the Indian Constitution is one of the most important
          and fundamental rights. It provides the Right to Life and Personal
          Liberty to every person. This article ensures that no person shall be
          deprived of their life or personal liberty except according to the
          procedure established by law.
        </p>
        <p>
          *The "Right to Life" under Article 21 is not just limited to mere
          survival or existence. It includes living a life with dignity, free
          from any inhuman or degrading treatment.
        </p>
        <p>
          * The "Right to Personal Liberty" means that every individual has the
          freedom to make personal choices and move freely without any
          unreasonable restrictions.
        </p>
        <p>
          *In Simple Words: Article 21 guarantees the right to live a life with
          dignity and personal freedom. It ensures that no one can be deprived
          of their life or liberty except through a fair, just, and legal
          process. This right has been interpreted to include many essential
          aspects of a meaningful life, such as privacy, health, a clean
          environment, and access to legal aid, making it a fundamental pillar
          of individual freedom and justice in India.
        </p>
      </div>
    </div>
