          Article 22: Protection Against Arrest and Detention in Certain Cases
        </h1>
        <p>
          *Article 22 of the Indian Constitution provides protection against
          arrest and detention in certain cases. It is a crucial safeguard for
          the protection of individual freedom and personal liberty, ensuring
          that no person is unlawfully detained or arrested
        </p>
        <p>
          * Any person who is arrested must be informed, as soon as possible, of
          the grounds for their arrest. This means they have a right to know why
          they are being detained.
        </p>
        <p>
          * The rights mentioned above (like being informed of the grounds of
          arrest and being produced before a magistrate) do not apply to cases
          of preventive detention.
        </p>
        <p>
          * In Simple Words Article 22 protects people from unlawful arrest and
          detention. It ensures that anyone arrested has the right to know why
          they are being arrested, to consult a lawyer, and to be brought before
          a magistrate within 24 hours. It also provides safeguards against
          preventive detention by limiting its duration and requiring oversight.
          This article helps protect personal freedom and prevents the abuse of
          power by law enforcement authorities.
        </p>
